  childSummary:"When you create a password for a website, the website doesn't actually SAVE your password — it puts it through a special math machine called a HASH that turns it into a jumbled code (like putting a document through a shredder). When you log in later, it shreds what you typed the SAME way and checks if the jumbled code matches. If it does, you're in! But passwords alone aren't super safe (people use easy ones like '123456'), so now most important accounts also ask for a SECRET CODE sent to your phone (called an OTP). This way, even if someone steals your password, they STILL can't get in without your phone! The newest and coolest way is called PASSKEYS — your phone uses your fingerprint or face to prove it's you, without any password at all!",
